  <billdetail>
    <title>Insurance (Prudential Supervision) Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Finance and Expenditure Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM3005100" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="95" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Finance and Expenditure Committee has examined the Insurance (Prudential Supervision) Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Insurance (Prudential Supervision) Bill seeks to reform and extend prudential supervision to cover the insurance industry. It would establish a system for licensing insurers, impose prudential requirements on insurers, provide for the supervision of compliance with those requirements by the Reserve Bank, and confer certain powers on the Reserve Bank to act in respect of insurers in financial or other difficulties. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The bill is intended to cover most entities that undertake insurance business in New Zealand, including life insurers, health insurers, captive insurers, re-insurers, and the insurance activities of incorporated societies. However, we are recommending that “discretionary mutual organisations” and trade or professional associations not be covered by the bill. This is discussed further below.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This commentary deals only with the substantive amendments we recommend to the bill; it does not discuss proposed technical, consequential, or minor drafting amendments. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Licensing of insurers</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Definitions of “contract of insurance” and “carrying on insurance business in New Zealand”</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend the deletion of clause 7(3) in order to clarify the application of the bill. The definition of “contract of insurance” in clause 7 is critical to the bill, and should be as clear as possible in its intent. In the bill as introduced, this subclause could be confusing for insurers as it could be interpreted to contradict subclause 7(1), and might widen the application of the bill beyond that which is currently considered to constitute insurance. Deleting the subclause would also result in the exemption of discretionary mutual organisations, which we consider accords with the policy intent of the bill. The exclusion of discretionary mutuals from the regime is discussed below.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend the inclusion of new clause 8(1)(a)(iia) to make it clearer that the definition of carrying on insurance business in New Zealand includes overseas persons that are not bodies corporate. In the bill as introduced, this clause would make the bill apply to all forms of legal entity (including credit unions, friendly societies, and other mutuals) and partnerships formed in New Zealand, though the status of an overseas person that was not a body corporate would be unclear. Our amendment would recognise that associations of persons formed outside New Zealand may be carrying on insurance business in New Zealand, meaning that they could be captured by the regime.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Exemptions for certain types of insurers</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend the insertion of new clause 229A to provide for regulations to be made exempting existing “small” insurers from certain requirements of the bill: financial strength ratings, statutory funds requirements, some requirements relating to financial reporting, and minimum capital requirements. Whilst these requirements would not apply to small insurers, other requirements of the bill would, including obtaining a licence, meeting fit and proper standards, risk management requirements, and appointing an actuary. We also recommend there be sufficient flexibility in the bill to apply special conditions of licence to small insurers on matters such as solvency. We consider that “small” insurers should be defined by the amount of their annual gross premium income; this amount would be specified in regulations, and is likely to be between $1 million and $1.5 million. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We are recommending the establishment of a graduated regime for small insurers because such entities could find a number of requirements in the full regime particularly onerous, to the point that it might put their viability at serious risk; and because no real benefit would be gained from applying the entire regime to small insurers. For this reason, we believe concessions to small existing insurers are justifiable. We also recommend that small insurers who become established after the passage of the bill into law not have access to this framework, unless they are friendly societies. This is in recognition of the Friendly Societies and Credit Union Act 1982, under which such insurers can form. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>For similar reasons, we also recommend that clause 8 be amended to exclude from coverage voluntary professional and trade organisations providing some insurance-type services to their members. Our proposed deletion of clause 7(3) would also provide exemptions to organisations offering discretionary benefits, which we consider should not be captured by the regime. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We propose the insertion of clause 8A, which would empower the Reserve Bank to declare that a person was not carrying on an insurance business in New Zealand where the person entered into a one-off or occasional contract of insurance and the bill’s requirements would be unduly onerous. This would allow the Reserve Bank to grant exemptions to persons entering into one-off insurance contracts that were secondary to their core business, which are not intended to be captured. After careful consideration, we recommend that declarations under this provision be subject to the Regulations (Disallowance) Act 1989, and recommend amendments to clause 228 accordingly. While we are assured that the Reserve Bank would put appropriate restrictions on the provision to ensure these declarations were not employed too widely, we consider that as they could cover a wide range of situations and it involves a power in the nature of an exemption, it should therefore be subject to disallowance by Parliament. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We considered carefully requests for complete or partial exemption from various kinds of other insurers, such as captive insurers and incorporated societies, including those entities that, while owned or controlled by professional or trade associations, are first and foremost insurance entities. However, we acknowledge that the bill is intended to capture all kinds of insurers to ensure they are subject to the same rules, and believe that size, rather than corporate form, should be the relevant criterion for exemption in order to make the regime workable. We therefore consider it would be inappropriate to exempt some forms of insurers and not others. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We are advised, however, that the three-year transition period available to insurers upon enactment of the bill would allow such entities ample opportunity to make changes to their business, structure, or other arrangements to enable them to comply with the regime. The Reserve Bank assured us that it would communicate with each insurer affected by the legislation, and could provide advice to insurers on these issues, should they require it. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Treatment of overseas insurers operating in New Zealand</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We considered carefully the effect of the bill on New Zealand insurers and overseas insurers, in response to concern that the proposed framework might unintentionally put New Zealand-owned insurers at a disadvantage, and the suggestion that more consistency was needed with overseas jurisdictions’ prudential frameworks, particularly that of Australia. We are assured, however, that the regime proposed in the bill would not disadvantage New Zealand insurers. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>In the bill as introduced, three clauses relate to exemptions for overseas insurers operating branches in New Zealand. Clause 36 allows the Reserve Bank to give exemptions in relation to “fit and proper” certificates for overseas directors, clause 60 allows exemptions from solvency standards, and clause 117 provides for exemptions from statutory fund requirements. These exemptions would be granted only if insurers operating branches in New Zealand were subject in their “home” jurisdiction to regulation that met the standards of the Reserve Bank; their standards would also, taken as a whole, have to be equivalent to New Zealand’s. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Exemptions provided to overseas insurers in these circumstances would confer no advantages relative to New Zealand insurers, because standards or requirements in the original jurisdiction comparable with New Zealand’s would be a condition of such exemption. Indeed, the exemptions would simply ensure that no duplication of regulation applied to overseas insurers operating in New Zealand. We believe that the alternative—excluding overseas insurers entirely from the bill—would not be appropriate, as it would leave them with no regulatory oversight in New Zealand; this is contrary to the intention of the bill, and would be more likely to confer advantages on overseas insurers relative to New Zealand ones. Excluding overseas insurers from selling insurance through their New Zealand branches would also reduce competition, and New Zealanders’ access to insurance. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We were advised that duplication of the Australian prudential framework in its entirety would be inappropriate, because New Zealand’s market has different requirements for supervision in some areas. Nevertheless, New Zealand’s framework draws heavily on Australia’s in some aspects, because of the similarities between the two countries, the number of insurers undertaking business in both countries, and Australia’s well-developed prudential regime. New Zealand’s framework would be tougher in some areas than Australia’s, but Australia’s would be tougher in others. For example, it is proposed that the New Zealand regime have higher risk-weights for unlisted equity investments, while Australia has much higher minimum capital requirements.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Because of certain grounds for exemptions discussed earlier, there was concern that the bill might create ambiguity in some areas, for example regarding solvency standards, where the standard of an overseas jurisdiction may be slightly lower than New Zealand’s, possibly causing uncertainty or unfairness. However, we are assured by the Reserve Bank that it would make careful judgements when considering these matters, and that the transition time for compliance with the legislation would allow enough flexibility for these issues to be resolved. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>However, we recommend an amendment to the bill in relation to overseas insurers. Because clause 18(1)(i) sets out criteria for the Reserve Bank to use to determine whether the home-jurisdiction prudential regulation and supervision of an overseas insurer was satisfactory, we consider that the regulations (made under clause 229) should prescribe in advance a list of overseas jurisdictions that are considered to regulate and supervise insurers satisfactorily to the level set out in the paragraph. This amendment would reduce uncertainty for insurers, and make the process less costly and more straightforward. The provisions in the bill as introduced could be interpreted to mean that the Reserve Bank would have to make a determination regarding the suitability of the jurisdiction in respect of each overseas insurer that applies for a licence, even when it had already considered another applicant from the same jurisdiction. We do not believe this would be an effective use of the Reserve Bank’s time and resources. Similar amendments are also proposed to clauses 36(2A) and 117(2A). </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Obtaining a licence</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend some minor amendments to the provisions governing the obtaining of an insurance licence. We recommend amending clause 16 to make it clear that only bodies corporate carrying on or proposing to carry on an insurance business in New Zealand are eligible to apply for a licence. This would make the criteria for licensing more explicit. It would also prevent overseas insurers from using New Zealand registration as a shelter for their overseas activities. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We propose some small amendments to clause 18(1). They would make it clear that the Reserve Bank must be satisfied that an applicant held capital of an amount specified in the solvency standard before that applicant was entitled to a licence. As one of the criteria for eligibility for a licence is a specified minimum amount of capital, we consider it important that the subclause refer to this requirement. We also propose an amendment to subclause (1)(j) to ensure that insurers that were not required to register under the Financial Service Providers (Registration and Dispute Resolution) Act 2008 would still be required to meet the standards set out in section 13(a) of that Act. These standards are an important factor in licensing decisions, and we consider that they should therefore also apply to entities that are not covered by the Act. We also recommend the removal of the reference to section 13(b) of the Financial Service Providers Act, because it is not relevant.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Licence conditions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending clause 20 to ensure that a solvency margin can be expressed in different ways, for example as an amount or as a ratio. This amendment is aimed at ensuring the provisions are workable for insurers, and that they are as easy to apply as possible. This clause is important because many of the thresholds for coercive action by the Reserve Bank relate to inability to maintain a solvency margin. We consider this amendment would help make sure the provision is effective. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend an amendment to clause 23(1) to clarify how and within what time a licensed insurer would have to inform the Reserve Bank if they believed they might fail to maintain a solvency margin. In the bill as introduced, the requirements and related timeframe are unclear; it says that the Reserve Bank must be informed “as soon as practicable” if an insurer is likely to fail “at any future time”. Accordingly, we propose the requirement that the Reserve Bank be informed as soon as reasonably practicable if a licensed insurer believes a failure to meet a solvency margin is likely within the next three years.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Notifying the Reserve Bank before obtaining control or changing corporate form</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amendments to clauses 25 to 27 to clarify that the person who intended to obtain the control would be the person responsible for informing the Reserve Bank about a change of control transaction, and to clarify what constitutes obtaining control. We propose that the duty should apply if a person was to become the “holding entity” of the insurer (which draws on sections 5 to 8 of the Companies Act 1993) or would (either alone or with others) obtain control over 50 percent or more of the voting rights in the insurer. The drafting of these clauses as introduced is unclear, especially as to who is the controlling owner and who must inform the Reserve Bank about the proposed change in control. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Fit and proper requirements</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend removing the detail in clauses 32(4) and 34 and allowing it to be specified by deemed regulation. Clause 32(4) includes the detailed requirements for assessing “fit and proper” persons, and clause 34 sets out some criteria for this purpose. Allowing this to be specified by deemed regulation would avoid any undue inflexibility resulting from enshrining the detail in legislation. Much of the detail of clause 34 is very prescriptive, and is more appropriate to be included in deemed regulations (“fit and proper standards”) where there is more scope for flexibility and variation. We consider that these standards should be subject to the Regulations (Disallowance) Act. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Transfers and amalgamations</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 44(1) to allow other suitably qualified persons to assist the Reserve Bank in making its assessment of a proposed transfer or amalgamation. As introduced, the subclause refers only to an independent actuary. While we consider that the opinion of an actuary would be the most relevant, we believe there would be merit in allowing other suitably qualified persons, such as accountants, to assist where the Reserve Bank considers it appropriate. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend an amendment to clause 45(1) to ensure it is clear that the Reserve Bank could obtain only reasonable costs from an insurer in relation to a report the bank had itself requested regarding approval for a transfer or amalgamation. This should reassure insurers that costs in this area are not intended to be excessive. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Lastly, we recommend an amendment to clause 47 to specify a time limit for the Reserve Bank of 20 working days from the day all reasonably required information is received regarding transfer or amalgamation applications. We believe that the requirement to secure approval should not obstruct legitimate transfers or amalgamations. No time limit is specified in the bill as introduced, and we believe that 20 working days should be sufficient. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Prudential regulations</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Solvency standards</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that clause 56 be widened to include some reporting against matters in the solvency standards that are not covered by reports produced under the Financial Reporting Act 1993. Broadening these provisions to allow the standards to require reports relating to solvency would ensure that all matters relating to solvency were taken into account in reporting. We also recommend that the clause be amended to allow the solvency standard to prescribe matters relating to minimum capital. Although the concept of minimum capital may be captured within the current formulation of solvency margin, our amendment would confirm this and provide the Reserve Bank with the means to impose solvency requirements. Solvency standards would be subject to the Regulations (Disallowance) Act. We also recommend amending clause 56 to make it clear that the solvency standard could cover disclosure matters and some reporting to the Reserve Bank and others in relation to solvency matters, and that offences would apply to breaches of these requirements. We consider this amendment necessary as the provision must encompass all matters that may be included in the solvency standard.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Because the Reserve Bank has completed substantial consultation on solvency standards, we also recommend that clause 228C, which requires such consultation before a solvency standard is issued, be amended to require consultation before the bill is passed to be treated as having been undertaken by the Reserve Bank for the purpose of this clause. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>While we do not have responsibility for the content of the regulations, we urge the Reserve Bank to ensure that solvency standards are fair. As explained earlier, solvency standards would be subject to the Regulations (Disallowance) Act. To that end, we recommend the insertion of new subclauses 53(3A) and 53(3B) which require the Reserve Bank, before issuing a solvency standard, to have regard to relevant overseas standards. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Some of us consider this is the minimum necessary to provide some reassurance to New Zealand-based insurers that the Reserve Bank will be closely watching issues posed by differing solvency standards applicable to insurance companies not incorporated in New Zealand. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Financial strength ratings</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that clause 61(2)(b) be amended to clarify that the reference to insurance business carried on by a reinsurer means an insurance business in New Zealand. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend a number of other small amendments regarding financial strength ratings provisions. We recommend that the bill be amended to require that a financial strength rating given by an approved ratings agency must refer to any overseas policyholder preference, as this is the intention. We also recommend that clauses 64 and 65 be amended to allow disclosure of a rating by an insurer through an intermediary. This would avoid further compliance costs and maintain continuity with the status quo.<footnote id="DLM3005101"><para><text>This position existed under the Insurance Companies (Ratings and Inspections) Act 1994. </text></para></footnote> We also recommend that clauses 64 and 65 be amended to impose a maximum penalty of $100,000, rather than the maximum $500,000 set out in clause 71, for breaching either of the clauses. We believe $500,000 is excessive and unwarranted in the context of the bill, and that $100,000 would be far more appropriate to these offences. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend two further amendments to clause 69. We recommend amending this clause to allow the insurer the option of using public notice of ratings downgrades as an alternative to formal written notice to all policyholders, which is the only option in the bill as introduced. We believe that this option could reduce compliance costs for insurers, while still ensuring that information relating to a change in rating was made public. We also recommend that the clause be amended to clarify that the requirement to give notice of a public downgrade of a rating would apply to all contracts, not just those with a duration of more than one year. This amendment would reflect the status quo under the Insurance Companies (Ratings and Inspections) Act 1994, and would be easier to comply with if our recommended amendment to allow public notice of a ratings downgrade were implemented. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Risk management plans</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 73 to allow, in extreme market circumstances only, notification to the Reserve Bank of a change to an insurer’s risk management plan after the change has been made. This amendment would require the insurer to notify the Reserve Bank as soon as possible after the change occurred, rather than to have the change pre-approved. We considered submissions advocating the removal of the requirement that the Reserve Bank pre-approve any change to a risk management plan; however, regulatory awareness and pre-approval of plans are important components of the prudential framework; in addition, such a move would open up the possibility of unwinding poorly-founded risk positions. Nonetheless, we are aware that in extreme circumstances immediate action on a plan could be needed, so we consider that the bill should provide for flexibility for an insurer to act quickly. Our proposed amendment would do so, while retaining the requirement for pre-approval in all other circumstances.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Appointment of actuary and actuarial review</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending clause 76(3) to allow insurers more time to appoint a new actuary if the Reserve Bank allows an extension. The clause as introduced allows six weeks for an insurer to make the new appointment; however, we believe that this should be extended to allow flexibility where an insurer could not meet the six-week deadline for good reason. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Finally, we recommend the deletion of clause 79(2), which requires the auditor’s report to indicate the degree of reliance that has been placed on the actuarial report. We believe that this subclause might be misunderstood as a qualification of the auditor’s opinion, and could therefore affect how the auditor’s report was viewed. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Supply of financial statements</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amendments to clause 81 to clarify some drafting issues. We recommend the insertion of new subclause 2A to make it clear that the definition of “subsidiaries” refers to the definition in section 2(1) of the Financial Reporting Act. We also recommend that subclause (3) be amended to require interim financial statements to be prepared according to generally accepted accounting practice (GAAP)—that is, the same way that yearly financial statements are prepared. The bill as introduced provides an option of using a basis other than GAAP, which we consider should be removed. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Statutory funds of life insurers</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>General requirements</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend a number of amendments to clause 84 to ensure consistency in the terminology used throughout the bill. Our amendments would replace the word “policyholder” in subclauses (1)(d)(ii) and (iii) with “insured person”. This would also clarify that the intended focus of the clause is on an insured person, rather than a policyholder. Further, we recommend that the phrase “specified sickness” in subclause (3)(b)(ii) be replaced with the phrase “stated condition or disease” for consistency with subclause (1)(d)(iii). </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend a further amendment to clause 84(1) to correct an omission. We propose including investment account contracts in the definition of a life policy, as such contracts are still in existence and so should be captured by the bill. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that clause 85 be amended to ensure that classification of composite policies into life and non-life policies is applied on a class of contract basis and according to the premium apportionment at the commencement of a contract. This amendment would allow these clauses to be applied more consistently. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 90(6) to change the transition time for insurers. Clause 90(6) provides that during the six months from the commencement of the clause, subclause (1) (which specifies that a policy document must identify the statutory fund or funds to which a life policy is referable) would not apply to a policy document relating to a life policy issued before the commencement of the clause. To ease the transition for insurers, we consider that the period should be increased to 12 months, so that insurers could capture every policy in their annual cycle. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend amendments to clause 97 of the bill, which relates to the limit of certain liabilities regarding investment performance guarantees. This clause is copied from Australian legislation, and is highly technical. We are aware of concern that the provision is difficult to interpret in places, and that some aspects of it are uncertain. We consider it appropriate to enable regulations to be made providing this detail, rather than providing it in primary legislation. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We propose one other amendment to clause 103(10). To provide assurance and clarity for directors, we consider that it should be made clear that compliance with directors’ duties to life policyholders would not put a director in breach of any other duty under the Companies Act or related obligations. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Transfer of assets on establishment of statutory funds</heading>
          <para>
            <text>To rectify an omission, we recommend that new clauses 88A and 91(ab) be inserted to provide for the transfer of assets upon the establishment of a statutory fund. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Application of statutory fund assets on liquidation or winding up</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 114(4) to allow the allocation of funds of an insolvent life insurer by direction of the High Court in cases where the statutory fund is insufficient to meet policyholder liabilities in full. In the bill as introduced, no direction is given for such situations; we consider it important to clarify this point to ensure certainty about the process if the situation arises. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Prudential supervision</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Disclosure of information by auditors and actuaries</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend two amendments to clause 125. For practical reasons, we recommend extending the clause to require past as well as present office-holders to disclose information about an insurer’s solvency and whether it may be operating fraudulently. We also recommend replacing references in the clause to “insolvency” with references to “failing to maintain a solvency margin”. This would link the clause clearly to the solvency margin imposed by condition of licence, as originally intended, rather than to actual solvency. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Confidentiality of information</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending clause 133 to ensure consistency between its subclauses. As introduced, subclause (1) refers to “information, data or forecasts”, and (2) refers only to information or data. We consider that the clause should be amended to refer consistently to data, information, forecasts, and documents. This amendment would also tighten up the confidentiality protections covering commercially sensitive information provided to the Reserve Bank. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Distress management</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Recovery plans</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amendments to clause 141 to require the Reserve Bank to consider whether a recovery plan should be requested in the particular circumstances before issuing a direction. This amendment would reflect the intention that a recovery plan should often be the first step in the distress management process, which can later be escalated to issuing directions or more serious measures. Because the Reserve Bank may need to act quickly in crises, however, we do not believe recovery plans should be a mandatory first step in the process.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Directions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending clause 142 so that various paragraphs in subclauses (1) and (2) are better aligned. These subclauses appear to contradict each other in the bill as introduced, as subclause (1)(d), for example, states that a direction may require a licensed insurer to cease to carry on its business or any part of its business, while subclause (2) instructs that a direction must not require the licensed insurer to cease to enter into contracts of insurance by way of renewal of contracts that were originally entered into before the direction was given. We therefore propose that subclause (2) begin with “However”, rather than “A”, to make it clear that subclause (1) is subject to subclause (2). </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Other matters</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Other definitions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>For clarification purposes, we recommend an amendment to clause 6 to make it clear that the financial strength rating refers only to the ability to meet liabilities under contracts of insurance. We are aware that there is some confusion over whether a financial strength rating refers to all liabilities rather than insurance policy liabilities only, so we consider that this clause needs to make it clear that the rating requirement is for financial strength and not for a credit rating. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Miscellaneous provisions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend a number of small amendments to the provisions relating to Lloyd’s (clauses 198 to 208) to clarify the respective obligations of Lloyd’s and Lloyd’s underwriters under the bill, to ensure that they can comply with the bill, and to allow Lloyd’s to be given a temporary licence pending the consideration of an application for a full licence. We also recommend that the provisions governing the application of the bill to Lloyd’s include a caveat in clause 203A(4) stating that Lloyd’s licence can be cancelled if it persistently or seriously breaches its obligations under the bill. The bill needs to include appropriate mechanisms to promote compliance by all insurers, including Lloyd’s. We consider that, in the case of Lloyd’s, cancellation is an appropriate mechanism. For similar reasons, we also consider that the bill should specify that there would be a sanction against Lloyd’s if a Lloyd’s underwriter were to enter into new insurance contracts in New Zealand following a direction under clause 205 not to do so. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend amending clause 217 to make it clear that if an insurer had a prohibited provision in its constitution allowing it to act in the best interests of its holding company even though it may not be in the best interests of the insurer, this is not deemed to be an offence, and deleting subclause (4) (detailing the fine for non-compliance). Clause 217 states that it is an offence for an insurer to have such a provision in its constitution. We consider that it would be better for non-complying insurers that the offending provision in their constitution should have no legal effect. This clause should also make it clear that it would apply only to New Zealand-incorporated companies. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Finally, we recommend amending clause 236 to include a reference to the ratings provisions in the bill as well as certain requirements under the Financial Reporting Act. The clause provides that provisional licence holders are required to comply with the requirements referred to in the clause only to the extent that the provisional licence conditions require compliance. Ratings provisions and certain Financial Reporting Act requirements are not included in this clause as introduced, meaning that insurers would have to be fully compliant with those requirements 18 months after the bill’s enactment. We consider that including the ratings and financial reporting requirements in this clause would make the transitional arrangements more flexible and avoid potential difficulties during this period. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Transitional matters</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend the insertion of subclause 229(1)(pa) to allow transitional provisions to be made for the coming into force of the statutory funds provisions in the bill (subpart 3 of Part 2). This would ensure that any unexpected consequences of the complexity of these provisions could be resolved. We recommend that this subclause be subject to a “sunset clause” limiting its existence to three years. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also recommend amending the transitional provisions to allow insurers to request approval from the Reserve Bank for a portfolio transfer with another insurer in the 18-month period following the enactment of the bill, before they would have received full or provisional licences. We consider this amendment necessary to maximise the time available for an insurer to change its business structure to meet the standards expected under the legislation. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Insurance (Prudential Supervision) Bill was referred to us on 8 December 2009. The closing date for submissions was 10 February 2010. We received and considered 57 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard 31 submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Reserve Bank of New Zealand. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
